    <!-- CRITICAL QUESTIONS TO RESOLVE -->
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-100">
            <h2 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">2. Critical Questions That Determine Migration Path</h2>
            
            <div style="background-color: #ffebee; border-left: 4px solid #d32f2f; padding: var(--spacing-medium); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <h3 style="color: #d32f2f; margin-top: 0;">❓ MUST CLARIFY BEFORE PROCEEDING</h3>
                
                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 15px;">✅ Question 1: Where is the production database 192.168.1.198?</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>ANSWER: Bare-metal server outside Proxmox with IP 192.168.1.198</strong></p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Implication:</strong> Production database runs on dedicated bare-metal infrastructure independent of Proxmox hypervisors. Network isolation requires careful K8s network policy configuration for StatefulSet access.</p>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 20px;">✅ Question 2: What is VMID 1002 (comserserver) on proxmoxws?</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>ANSWER: Reserved for future use as production Catalyst application server (not part of database migration)</strong></p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Implication:</strong> VMID 1002 is out of scope for this database migration. Future Catalyst application scaling may utilize this VM for multi-instance deployment.</p>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 20px;">✅ Question 3: What is VMID 500 (mysqlserver) on proxmoxws?</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>ANSWER: Originally created as production database, but not needed for this migration (non-Docker approach). Retain as backup.</strong></p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Implication:</strong> VMID 500 serves as a disaster recovery backup. Not part of K8s migration path, but maintain as fallback option.</p>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 20px;">✅ Question 4: Existing K8s Setup</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>ANSWER: Use existing K8s nodes as-is to leverage work already completed. Original intent was for production Catalyst.</strong></p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Context:</strong> K8s master/worker nodes were started for implementation but have not been changed in some time with no active use.</p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Clarifying Note:</strong> Do each application server instance (if scaled) need its own K8s master/worker nodes, or can multiple Catalyst instances share the same cluster?</p>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Implication:</strong> Existing K8s cluster will host both MariaDB StatefulSet and future Catalyst application deployments. Single cluster design simplifies operations.</p>
            </div>

            <p style="text-align: right; margin-top: var(--spacing-small);"><a href="#toc" style="color: var(--link-color); font-size: var(--font-size-small);">↑ Back to Top</a></p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DUAL-DB SYNC STRATEGY -->
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-100">
            <h2 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">3. Dual-Database Sync Strategy During Migration</h2>
            
            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Instead of a risky big-bang cutover, keep both 192.168.1.198 and Kubernetes databases in sync during migration period.</p>

            <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Option A: Using Application-Level Priority (Recommended)</h3>
            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Leverage the existing <code>db_config.json</code> priority system in Comserv.</p>

            <div style="background-color: #e3f2fd; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 0;">Phase 1: Both DBs Running (Weeks 1-4)</h4>
                <pre style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: 10px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-color); overflow-x: auto;"><code>
# db_config.json priority order (DURING MIGRATION):
Priority 1: 192.168.1.198 (production_server) - CURRENT LIVE DB - Reads & Writes
Priority 2: mariadb.comserv-prod.svc.cluster.local - NEW K8S DB - REPLICA (Reads only)
Priority 3-N: Other fallbacks...

# How this works:
1. Application connects to 192.168.1.198 first
2. If it fails, tries K8s database
3. All writes go to 192.168.1.198 (source of truth)
4. K8s database replicates from 192.168.1.198 via MySQL replication
                </code></pre>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 15px;">Implementation Steps:</h4>
                <ol style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); line-height: 1.8;">
                    <li><strong>Set up MySQL replication</strong>: Configure 192.168.1.198 as primary, K8s MariaDB pods as replicas</li>
                    <li><strong>Verify replication lag</strong>: Monitor <code>SHOW SLAVE STATUS\G</code> - ensure Seconds_Behind_Master &lt; 1</li>
                    <li><strong>Test failover</strong>: Manually set Priority 1 to K8s DB, verify app works, revert</li>
                    <li><strong>Run monitoring</strong>: Alert if replication lag exceeds 5 seconds</li>
                </ol>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 15px;">Advantages:</h4>
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
                    <li>Zero app code changes required</li>
                    <li>Automatic fallback if K8s DB has issues</li>
                    <li>Gradual confidence building during testing period</li>
                    <li>Can abort migration at any time during week 1-4</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); margin-top: 20px;">Option B: Database-Level Replication (Master-Master)</h3>
            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Set both databases to accept writes, replicate in both directions.</p>

            <div style="background-color: #f3e5f5; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 0;">When to Use This Approach</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Only if you need to:</p>
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
                    <li>Distribute writes across both databases</li>
                    <li>Test K8s database thoroughly before full cutover</li>
                </ul>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 15px;">⚠️ Complexity Warnings</h4>
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
                    <li><strong>UUID conflicts:</strong> Auto-increment IDs must be carefully managed (use UUID v4 instead)</li>
                    <li><strong>Write conflicts:</strong> Same record modified on both DBs simultaneously → requires conflict resolution logic</li>
                    <li><strong>Operational overhead:</strong> Monitoring, debugging is significantly more complex</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Use Option A (Application-level priority) instead. Simpler and safer.</p>
            </div>

            <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); margin-top: 20px;">Option C: Canary Deployment (Gradual Traffic Shift)</h3>
            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Route percentage of reads to K8s DB, keep all writes on 192.168.1.198.</p>

            <div style="background-color: #ede7f6; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 0;">Timeline</h4>
                <pre style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: 10px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-color);">
Week 3: 192.168.1.198 primary, K8s replica
        All writes → 192.168.1.198
        Reads → 100% to 192.168.1.198, 0% to K8s

Week 4, Day 1: Increase K8s read traffic
        Reads → 95% to 192.168.1.198, 5% to K8s (test with non-critical queries)

Week 4, Day 2: More K8s reads
        Reads → 80% to 192.168.1.198, 20% to K8s

Week 4, Day 3: K8s fully online
        Reads → 100% to K8s DB
        Writes → Still 100% to 192.168.1.198

Week 5: Final cutover (writes to K8s)
        Reads & Writes → 100% to K8s DB
        Keep 192.168.1.198 as fallback for 3 days
                </pre>

                <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); margin-top: 15px;">Implementation:</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Modify Comserv's <code>RemoteDB.pm</code> to support percentage-based routing:</p>
                <pre style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: 10px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-color); overflow-x: auto;"><code>
# pseudo-code for RemoteDB.pm
sub get_connection {
    my ($self, $readonly) = @_;
    
    if ($readonly) {
        # Read-only queries: use percentage routing
        my $rand = int(rand(100));
        if ($rand < 20) {  # 20% to K8s
            return $self->_connect_k8s_replica();
        } else {           # 80% to 192.168.1.198
            return $self->_connect_baremetal();
        }
    } else {
        # Write queries: always use primary
        return $self->_connect_baremetal();  # 192.168.1.198
    }
}
                </code></pre>
            </div>

            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Recommendation for your case:</strong> Start with Option A (Application priority), then implement Option C (Canary) for final cutover if risk tolerance is high.</p>

            <p style="text-align: right; margin-top: var(--spacing-small);"><a href="#toc" style="color: var(--link-color); font-size: var(--font-size-small);">↑ Back to Top</a></p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- USING APP SCHEMA SYSTEM -->
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-100">
            <h2 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">4. Leveraging Comserv Schema System for Migration</h2>
            
            <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">The Comserv application already has infrastructure to handle database configuration changes. We can use this.</p>

            <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Where Configuration Lives</h3>
            <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <tr style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
                    <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Config Source</strong></th>
                    <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Location</strong></th>
                    <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Used During Migration</strong></th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><code>db_config.json</code> (Priority-based)</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">File on disk or K8s mounted volume</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">✅ YES - primary routing mechanism</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color;">Environment Variables (<code>COMSERV_DB_*</code>)</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Set in docker-compose or K8s deployment</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">✅ YES - override json file</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><code>RemoteDB.pm</code> (Connection logic)</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Code: <code>lib/Comserv/Model/RemoteDB.pm</code></td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">✅ YES - add custom logic here</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Schema Comparison UI (<code>/admin/compare_schema</code>)</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Admin controller endpoint</td>
                    <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">✅ YES - verify sync between DBs</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); margin-top: 20px;">Migration Configuration Strategy</h3>

            <div style="background-color: #e8f5e9; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 0;">Step 1: Update db_config.json (Weeks 1-3)</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Add K8s database as Priority 2:</p>
                <pre style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: 10px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-color); overflow-x: auto;"><code>
{
  "production_server": {
    "db_type": "mariadb",
    "host": "192.168.1.198",  ← PRIMARY (live)
    "port": 3306,
    "username": "shanta_forager",
    "password": "UA=nPF8*m+T#",
    "database": "ency",
    "priority": 1  ← HIGHEST
  },
  
  "k8s_galera_primary": {
    "db_type": "mariadb",
    "host": "mariadb.comserv-prod.svc.cluster.local",  ← REPLICA
    "port": 3306,
    "username": "shanta_forager",
    "password": "UA=nPF8*m+T#",
    "database": "ency",
    "priority": 2  ← FALLBACK (read-only)
  },
  
  // ... other existing entries
}
                </code></pre>

                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 15px;">Step 2: Set MySQL Replication (Week 2-3)</h4>
                <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">Configure 192.168.1.198 as replication master, K8s pods as replicas.</p>
                <pre style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: 10px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-color); overflow-x: auto;"><code>
# On 192.168.1.198 (primary):
mysql> GRANT REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO 'repl'@'%.%.%.%' IDENTIFIED BY 'repl_password';
mysql> FLUSH BINARY LOGS;
mysql> SHOW MASTER STATUS;
# Save: File: mysql-bin.000001, Position: 154

# On K8s mariadb-0 pod (replica):
kubectl exec -it mariadb-0 -n comserv-prod -- mysql -u root -p << EOF
CHANGE MASTER TO
  MASTER_HOST='192.168.1.198',
  MASTER_PORT=3306,
  MASTER_USER='repl',
  MASTER_PASSWORD='repl_password',
  MASTER_LOG_FILE='mysql-bin.000001',
  MASTER_LOG_POS=154;

START SLAVE;
SHOW SLAVE STATUS\G
